e experience of disease, burial, surgery and wounds, medicine, hospitals, trauma, military welfare, widowhood, desertion, imprisonment and charity. The percentage population loss in these conflicts was far higher than that of the two World Wars, which renders the Civil Wars arguably the most unsettling experience the British people have ever undergone. The volume explores its themes from new angles, demonstrating how military history can broaden its perspective and reach out to new audiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical carexHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMedical carezGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aMedical personnelxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMedical personnelzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aMedicine, MilitaryxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMedicine, MilitaryzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 0aMortalityxHistoryx17th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aMortalityzGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aburial.  adisease.  amedicine.  asoldiers.  asurgery.  awelfare.  awidows.  awounds.1 aAppleby, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAppleby, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAtherton, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopper, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHopper, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJennings, Stuart B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangley, Chris R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPells, Ismini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g